      "writtenOn": "2026-04-07T06:19:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "@ed@tanous.net\nProblem Statement:\nCurrently, bmcweb uses a single SSL context for all connections, which\ncreates certificate management conflicts\n\n1. By default, bmcweb generates self-signed HTTPS certificates for\n   web console and management tool access.\n\n2. In data centers, customers upload CA-signed HTTPS certificates to\n   replace the self-signed certificates for secure BMC access.\n\n3. For Redfish aggregation in future system designs, peer BMCs need\n   mutual TLS (mTLS) authentication using certificates provisioned in\n   TPM (Trusted Platform Module).\n\n4. The mTLS certificates for peer BMC communication must be independent\n   from HTTPS certificates used by HMC/GUI clients, as they serve\n   different security domains and have different lifecycle management:\n   - HTTPS certs: Customer-managed, replaced during deployment\n   - mTLS certs: TPM-provisioned \n\nThe single SSL context architecture prevents using different certificate\nsets for these two distinct use cases.\n\nTechnical Challenge:\nSSL context selection must occur during TLS Client Hello processing,\nbefore certificate exchange. At this point in the handshake (RFC 5246),\nthe only client-provided routing signal available is the SNI (Server\nName Indication) extension. Client certificates arrive later in the\nhandshake, after the SSL context is already locked in.\n\nSolution:\nImplement dual SSL contexts with SNI-based routing:\n\n1. HTTPS Context (default):\n   - Used for web console, HMC, GUI, and management tools\n   - Uses certificates from /etc/ssl/certs/https/server.pem\n   - No client certificate required (verify_none)\n   - Activated for all connections except those with SNI \"mtls.bmc\"\n\n2. mTLS Context (peer BMC communication):\n   - Used for Redfish aggregation between peer BMCs\n   - Uses certificates from /etc/ssl/certs/https/server_bmc.pem\n   - Client certificate required (verify_peer | verify_fail_if_no_peer_cert)\n   - Activated when client sends SNI hostname \"mtls.bmc\"\n   - Certificates provisioned in TPM,(currently tested with filesystems, until TPM support for certs in place) independent lifecycle\n\n TLS Handshake Order (RFC 5246) :\n1. Client Hello (contains SNI extension) ← ONLY TIME TO SWITCH CONTEXT\n2. Server Hello (server selects certificate)\n3. Server Certificate\n4. Server Key Exchange\n5. Certificate Request (server asks for client cert)\n6. Client Certificate ← TOO LATE, context already selected\n7. Client Key Exchange\n8. Certificate Verify\n\nThe SNI-based approach is necessary because:\n- Context selection must happen at Client Hello time (step 1 of handshake)\n- Client certificate arrives at step 6, too late for context switching\n- Alternative approaches (separate ports, certificate detection) are not\n  viable due to timing constraints and resource considerations\n\n\nCertificate Independence:\nEach SSL context maintains its own certificate chain, allowing:\n- HTTPS certificates to be updated without affecting mTLS connections\n- mTLS certificates to be updated without affecting HTTPS connections\n- Different CAs for each certificate type\n- Independent certificate expiration and renewal cycles\n\nBackward Compatibility:\nExisting clients are unaffected:\n- Connections without \"mtls.bmc\" SNI use standard HTTPS context\n- No changes required for HMC, GUI, or management tools\n\nImplementation Details:\n- SslContextPair structure holds both HTTPS and mTLS contexts\n- Client Hello callback examines SNI and switches context if needed\n- Preserves existing verify callback during context switch\n- Uses OpenSSL ex_data mechanism for context pair storage\n- RAII-based memory management with custom shared_ptr deleter\n\nTesting:\nVerified on two peer BMC with the following scenarios:\n\n1. mTLS connections with independent certificates:\n   Peer BMC connections with SNI \"mtls.bmc\" use mTLS context\n   mTLS certificates from /etc/ssl/certs/https/server_bmc.pem\n   Client certificate verification enforced (tlsstrict \u003d true)\n   mTLS certificates independent of HTTPS certificates\n\n\n2. HTTPS certificate replacement without mTLS impact:\n   Uploaded CA-signed HTTPS certificate to replace self-signed cert\n   HMC/GUI connections use new HTTPS certificate\n   Peer BMC mTLS connections continue using original mTLS certificate\n   No disruption to mTLS aggregation during HTTPS cert update\n   Both certificate types coexist independently\n\n3. mTLS certificate update without HTTPS impact:\n   Updated mTLS certificate in /etc/ssl/certs/https/server_bmc.pem\n   Peer BMC connections use new mTLS certificate\n   HMC/GUI HTTPS connections continue using original HTTPS certificate\n   No disruption to web console during mTLS cert update\n   Certificate updates are isolated to their respective contexts\n\n4. Mixed client scenarios:\n   HMC/GUI clients (no SNI): HTTPS context, no client cert required\n   Management tools (SNI\u003dhostname): HTTPS context, standard TLS\n   Peer BMCs (SNI\u003d\"mtls.bmc\"): mTLS context, mutual authentication\n   All client types work simultaneously without interference   \n\nUse Case: Redfish Aggregation in Data Centers\nIn production deployments:\n- Aggregator BMC manages multiple satellite BMCs\n- Satellite BMCs connect using mTLS with TPM-provisioned certificates(this patch uses file system until we have TPM cert in place)\n- Customers upload CA-signed HTTPS certificates for web access\n- Both certificate types must coexist without conflicts\n- Certificate updates must not disrupt the other connection type\n\nThis implementation enables secure peer BMC communication while\nmaintaining standard HTTPS access for management interfaces, with\ncomplete certificate independence between the two security domains.",
      "parentUuid": "816fbd6d_e10e9c58",
      "revId": "ffe83055a4098639ff087f1a2216088462475114",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
