      "message": "As an aside, I\u0027m having a lot of trouble responding to you given the wall of text above.  Please make sure your commit message has a SUCCINCT version of the problem statement, what you are trying to accomplish, and what specifications you\u0027re trying to implement (namely SNI).  Lots of details on WHAT the change is doing isn\u0027t needed, as we can see that from the code.  we need a good explanation of WHY you\u0027re doing it, and what you expect the result to be.\n\n\u003e Currently, bmcweb uses a single SSL context for all connections\n\nThis is verifiably not true, as you can see in the diff, there are already two, one for incoming connections and one for outgoing\n```\nstd::shared_ptr\u003cboost::asio::ssl::context\u003e getSslServerContext();\n\nstd::optional\u003cboost::asio::ssl::context\u003e getSSLClientContext(\n    VerifyCertificate verifyCertificate);\n```\n\n\u003e HTTPS certs: Customer-managed, replaced during deployment\nmTLS certs: TPM-provisioned\n\nLets call these server certificates, and client certificates, because that\u0027s what the code calls it.\n\u003e For Redfish aggregation in future system designs, peer BMCs need\nmutual TLS (mTLS) authentication using certificates provisioned in\nTPM (Trusted Platform Module).\n\nHow does that work if the private keys are in the TPM?\n\n\n\u003e HTTPS context, standard TLS\nPeer BMCs (SNI\u003d\"mtls.bmc\")\n\nWhere in the TLS specification is \"mtls.bmc\" specified.  This looks to be a violation of SNI, and it should be set to the hostname of the connection in question.",
