      "message": "Hi @ed@tanous.net, \n\nThanks for your patience. Based on your feedback that SNI can use IP addresses, I’ve redesigned the solution to be RFC compliant while maintaining security.\n\nKey changes:\n- Removed the \"mtls.bmc\" now SNI uses actual satellite IP addresses.\n- Add satellite authorization list; only configured satellites can use mTLS( this can be addressed as a different patch)\n- Two-layer security: IP detection + satellite list validation(as aseperate patch).\n- RFC 6066 compliant: SNI contains actual destination IP/hostname.\n\nCritical code change:\nPreviously, SNI was skipped for IP addresses. Now, SNI is always set, even for IPs, enabling proper satellite mTLS detection.\n\nBelow code will be changed for IP address set for SNI:\nif (host.host_type() !\u003d boost::urls::host_type::name)\n        {           \n            // Avoid setting SNI hostname if its IP address\n            return;\n        }  \nThus the change will have \n- RFC compliant and secure.\n- Explicit authorization via satellite list(can be addressed in seperate patch).\n- Backward compatible with existing HTTPS connections.\n\nNext steps:\nI’ll upload the updated patchset to Gerrit with the testscript executed, once you confirm this direction looks good.\n\nAwaiting for your confirmation?\n\nThanks",
